{
  "text": "Dengue virus (DENV) is the leading arthropod-borne viral infection in the world, and represents a major global human health concern. DENV is endemic in more than 100 countries with up to 3 billion people in tropical regions of the world at risk of infection [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Recently, DENV has expanded its global range, with longterm outbreaks in South America and reintroduction into North America through Florida and Texas, with each of these outbreaks accompanied by increased disease severity. Of the estimated 50-100 million annual cases, the majority of infected individuals develop a self-limiting febrile illness, but approximately 500,000 clinical cases result in more severe manifestations, such as DENVinduced hemorrhagic fever and shock syndrome [CITATION_4] , leading to 25-50,000 deaths per year [CITATION_5] . The pathogenesis of dengue is incompletely understood and the factors that determine whether infection manifests as self-limiting dengue fever or progresses to life-threatening illness remains unanswered.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "11274077",
    "[CITATION_2]": "11733469",
